Citations
Date:  28/10/1933
Source:  Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page:  17
Edition:
Quote:  Hunt down. To hunt the sheep off the higher parts of their winter country on to lower, safer spurs when snow is expected, e.g., `We hunted down every day for a week, but no snow came.' This is a very common expression in the Lakes district of Otago. i cannot remember hearing it in

Canterbury, though the job is done often enough. (C,1918)
Notes:  Acland Glossary

Date:  0/0/1966
Source:  Boss's Story, The
Author:  NEWTO
Vol / Page:  188
Edition:
Quote:   Hunting down: Where sheep are wintered on high unfenced country subject to snow it is a common practice to keep them hunted down from the higher, more dangerous snow levels.
Notes:

